1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:04,880
This is what beginner traders think 
a professional chart looks like. 

2
00:00:04,880 --> 00:00:09,200
And this... is what a professional 
chart actually looks like. 

3
00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:13,920
The pros don't use chaos, they 
use confluence…a simple system  

4
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:17,680
where one static level and one dynamic one meet,  

5
00:00:17,680 --> 00:00:23,581
to create a trading 'sweet spot'.
Today I'm giving you the entire system…

6
00:00:23,581 --> 00:00:24,720
The Two-Level Rule
So let me show you  

7
00:00:24,720 --> 00:00:28,240
something that's going to 
change how you trade forever. 

8
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:34,960
Remember this: price only respects 
two things in this market. Just two. 

9
00:00:34,960 --> 00:00:40,640
Static levels that never move, and 
dynamic levels that flow with price. 

10
00:00:40,640 --> 00:00:45,120
That's it. Everything else is 
noise designed to confuse you. 

11
00:00:45,120 --> 00:00:48,880
Think about what's really 
happening behind these candles. 

12
00:00:48,880 --> 00:00:52,160
Every move you see is either 
bouncing off a level from the  

13
00:00:52,160 --> 00:00:59,280
past… that's your static support and resistance.
Or is riding along a moving barrier that shifts  

14
00:00:59,280 --> 00:01:04,640
with the trend…that's your dynamic level.
The market is just ping-ponging  

15
00:01:04,640 --> 00:01:10,720
between these two forces constantly.
So here's the mental shift that changes  

16
00:01:10,720 --> 00:01:17,920
everything. Stop looking for complex patterns.
Start looking for where these two forces meet. 

17
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:25,440
When a static level that's been tested multiple 
times crosses paths with a dynamic moving average,  

18
00:01:25,440 --> 00:01:31,040
you get what I call a confluence zone.
This is where the magic happens. 

19
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:37,840
The technique is dead simple. You mark your 
horizontal levels where price has bounced before. 

20
00:01:37,840 --> 00:01:42,000
Then you add one moving average 
that flows with the trend. 

21
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:47,920
When these two intersect, you have a zone 
where institutional traders are watching. 

22
00:01:47,920 --> 00:01:54,560
And suddenly you can see exactly where price 
has to make a decision. No confusion. No  

23
00:01:54,560 --> 00:02:00,720
conflicting signals. Just clean, obvious 
zones where something has to happen. 

24
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:06,446
You just learned the foundation 
that most beginners never discover.

25
00:02:06,446 --> 00:02:08,400
How to Identify Your Static Levels
Now let's talk about finding the  

26
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:10,560
levels that actually matter. 

27
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:15,520
Not every horizontal line on your chart 
is worth trading. Most of them are just  

28
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:20,560
noise. You need to find the levels 
where real money has changed hands. 

29
00:02:20,560 --> 00:02:27,440
Here's the touch test. Look for levels where 
price has bounced at least one before. Each  

30
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:35,040
time price hits a level and reverses, it's like 
the market is voting. This level has power. 

31
00:02:35,040 --> 00:02:40,400
Also, pay special attention to round 
numbers. These psychological levels  

32
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:47,920
work because human psychology doesn't change. 
Traders place orders at these obvious numbers,  

33
00:02:47,920 --> 00:02:53,920
creating natural support and resistance.
But here's what most people get wrong. They  

34
00:02:53,920 --> 00:03:01,760
think a level has to be exact. They draw a line at 
one level and expect price to bounce to the pip.  

35
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:06,720
That's not how markets work.
Think zones, not lines.  

36
00:03:06,720 --> 00:03:12,080
Give your level some breathing room. 
Maybe 5 to 10 pips above and below. 

37
00:03:12,080 --> 00:03:17,120
And here's a key point about timing. 
Recent levels carry more weight than  

38
00:03:17,120 --> 00:03:23,920
ancient history. A level that worked yesterday 
is more relevant than one from last week. The  

39
00:03:23,920 --> 00:03:31,360
market has memory, but it's not perfect memory.
Don't mark every swing high and low on your chart.  

40
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:36,080
Find the most recent 3 or 4 
levels that really stand out.  

41
00:03:36,080 --> 00:03:44,047
The ones where you can see clear rejections.
That's how you find levels that actually matter.

42
00:03:44,047 --> 00:03:46,880
Choosing the Right Moving Average
Let's talk about your dynamic level.  

43
00:03:46,880 --> 00:03:52,960
This is the line that's going to flow with the 
trend and give you context for every trade. 

44
00:03:52,960 --> 00:03:57,920
I'm going to save you years of testing different 
moving averages. Use the 50 EMA. That's it. The 50  

45
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:05,920
exponential moving average is your best friend.
Why 50? It's fast enough to catch trend changes  

46
00:04:05,920 --> 00:04:10,400
but slow enough to filter out 
noise. It responds to price  

47
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:18,240
movements quickly without whipsawing you to death.
For this strategy, we want this faster response. 

48
00:04:18,240 --> 00:04:24,240
Here's how to read your moving average. Look 
at the angle. If it's pointing up steeply,  

49
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:30,320
you've got a strong uptrend. Price should 
bounce when it touches this line. If it's  

50
00:04:30,320 --> 00:04:37,520
pointing down steeply, strong downtrend. Look 
for short opportunities when price touches. 

51
00:04:37,520 --> 00:04:42,618
If the moving average is flat, you're 
in a range. The trend is weak or  

52
00:04:42,618 --> 00:04:48,000
nonexistent. Static levels become 
more important in these conditions. 

53
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:54,720
One practical tip - make your moving average 
stand out visually. You want to see it clearly  

54
00:04:54,720 --> 00:05:01,575
when you're scanning charts. This line is 
going to guide most of your trading decisions.

55
00:05:01,575 --> 00:05:04,800
The Confluence Sweet Spot
Now we get to the magic moment. When your static  

56
00:05:04,800 --> 00:05:11,520
level and your moving average come together.
Perfect confluence happens when these two levels  

57
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:18,000
intersect within about 10 pips of each other.
Picture this - price is falling toward your  

58
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:24,880
support level, and right at that same spot, 
your 50 EMA is providing dynamic support. 

59
00:05:24,880 --> 00:05:30,800
Two reasons for price to bounce instead of one.
But you don't need perfect alignment  

60
00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:34,000
to make money.
Near-miss zones work  

61
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:41,600
beautifully too. If your static level and moving 
average are within 15 to 20 pips of each other,  

62
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:48,560
you still have a tradable confluence zone.
Here's the key rule for direction. You only trade  

63
00:05:48,560 --> 00:05:55,200
bounces in the direction of your moving average 
slope. If the line is angled up, you only look  

64
00:05:55,200 --> 00:06:01,760
for buy opportunities at confluence support.
If it's angled down, you only look for sell  

65
00:06:01,760 --> 00:06:08,160
opportunities at confluence resistance.
When price approaches your confluence zone,  

66
00:06:08,160 --> 00:06:14,640
watch for the rejection signal. You want to 
see price "kiss and bounce." It touches the  

67
00:06:14,640 --> 00:06:20,480
zone and immediately reverses. 
Like it hit an invisible wall. 

68
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:27,920
Sometimes price will poke through the zone 
slightly before bouncing. That's normal. Remember,  

69
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:35,405
we're thinking in zones, not exact lines. A 
small breach doesn't invalidate the level.

70
00:06:35,405 --> 00:06:37,840
Entry Rules (Only Trade the Bounce)
Let's get precise about when and  

71
00:06:37,840 --> 00:06:42,320
how to enter these trades.
First, price has to come to  

72
00:06:42,320 --> 00:06:48,880
your confluence zone. You can't chase price 
to the zone. You have to let it come to you. 

73
00:06:48,880 --> 00:06:54,480
Once price reaches your confluence area, 
you wait for the bounce confirmation.  

74
00:06:54,480 --> 00:07:00,480
You need to see price reject the zone and 
start moving away from it. A quick touch  

75
00:07:00,480 --> 00:07:06,320
and reversal is what you're looking for.
Here's your entry rule. You enter after a  

76
00:07:06,320 --> 00:07:12,960
candle closes away from the confluence zone. Not 
when it touches. Not when it's still inside the  

77
00:07:12,960 --> 00:07:20,640
zone. After a full candle closes in your favor.
This confirmation candle eliminates most of the  

78
00:07:20,640 --> 00:07:27,280
false signals. It proves that the bounce 
is real, not just a temporary pause. 

79
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:34,640
Direction is crucial. At support confluence zones, 
you only buy. At resistance confluence zones,  

80
00:07:34,640 --> 00:07:42,640
you only sell. Never try to pick tops in an 
uptrend or catch falling knives in a downtrend. 

81
00:07:42,640 --> 00:07:48,800
For every trade, your stop loss goes just 
outside the confluence zone. For a buy,  

82
00:07:48,800 --> 00:07:55,920
place it 10 pips below support. For a 
sell, 10 pips above resistance. This is  

83
00:07:55,920 --> 00:08:02,720
your safety net. You never trade without it. 
And you target double the amount you risked. 

84
00:08:02,720 --> 00:08:10,320
And here's what separates this strategy from 
others - you only trade bounces. Never breakouts.  

85
00:08:10,320 --> 00:08:16,640
If price breaks through your confluence zone, 
you do nothing. You wait for the next setup. 

86
00:08:16,640 --> 00:08:21,760
Breakout trading requires different 
skills and different risk management.  

87
00:08:21,760 --> 00:08:28,000
We're bounce traders. We profit from 
zones holding, not from zones breaking. 

88
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:34,800
Your entry should feel natural. When you see the 
setup forming, when price approaches confluence,  

89
00:08:34,800 --> 00:08:40,320
when you get that bounce confirmation - it 
should feel obvious. If you're forcing the  

90
00:08:40,320 --> 00:08:46,370
trade or second-guessing yourself, 
it's probably not the right setup.

91
00:08:46,370 --> 00:08:48,240
“Perfect Confluence” Trade
Let me show you what a textbook  

92
00:08:48,240 --> 00:08:53,920
confluence setup looks like in action.
We've got a clear support level here,  

93
00:08:53,920 --> 00:09:01,600
former resistance. It’s a strong static level.
Now watch what happens. Price is trending higher,  

94
00:09:01,600 --> 00:09:10,000
and our 50 EMA is angled up, providing dynamic 
support. As price pulls back, the line starts  

95
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:16,240
converging with our static support level.
Perfect alignment. This is confluence  

96
00:09:16,240 --> 00:09:19,040
at its finest.
Price approaches the  

97
00:09:19,040 --> 00:09:26,160
zone from above…it touches the confluence area 
and immediately rejects higher. Look at that  

98
00:09:26,160 --> 00:09:33,520
bounce candle - strong body, small lower wick. 
The market is showing respect for this zone. 

99
00:09:33,520 --> 00:09:38,000
Entry comes on the next candle 
after we get confirmation. 

100
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:45,200
This is what happens when multiple support factors 
align. The probability of success goes way up. 

101
00:09:45,200 --> 00:09:51,440
The institutions see the same confluence you 
see. They're placing orders in the same area. 

102
00:09:51,440 --> 00:09:57,200
These perfect confluence trades like this 
don't come every hour. But when they do,  

103
00:09:57,200 --> 00:10:00,139
they tend to work beautifully.

104
00:10:00,139 --> 00:10:01,120
“Near-Miss” Trade
Now, you don't  

105
00:10:01,120 --> 00:10:07,760
need perfect alignment to make money.
Here's Pound Yen on the 4-hour chart. We have  

106
00:10:07,760 --> 00:10:15,600
a key level here - you can see a previous support, 
turning into resistance. So clear static level. 

107
00:10:15,600 --> 00:10:22,080
The moving average is angled down, showing the 
downtrend. But notice, the moving average is  

108
00:10:22,080 --> 00:10:29,360
about 20 pips below our resistance level. 
Not perfect confluence, but close enough. 

109
00:10:29,360 --> 00:10:36,880
Next, price rallies into this zone and starts 
to reverse. The rejection isn't as sharp as our  

110
00:10:36,880 --> 00:10:42,720
perfect confluence example, but it's still clear.
Now you might ask, why did this  

111
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:48,160
work even without perfect alignment?
Because the market was seeing the same resistance  

112
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:56,240
zone we were. The static level plus the nearby 
moving average created enough selling pressure. 

113
00:10:56,240 --> 00:11:02,320
Zone thinking is crucial for this strategy. 
Don't get hung up on exact prices. Look  

114
00:11:02,320 --> 00:11:08,000
for areas where multiple support or 
resistance factors cluster together. 

115
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:14,480
Near-miss setups like this actually outnumber 
perfect confluence trades. If you only waited  

116
00:11:14,480 --> 00:11:20,541
for perfect alignment, you'd miss 
a lot of profitable opportunities.

117
00:11:20,541 --> 00:11:21,760
Strong Trend Bounce
Now let me show you  

118
00:11:21,760 --> 00:11:28,080
confluence in a strong trending market. 
This is where the strategy really shines. 

119
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:33,520
Dow Jones Index, 1-hour chart. Clear 
uptrend with a steep moving average  

120
00:11:33,520 --> 00:11:40,480
angle. This line is acting like a perfect 
trend line, supporting every pullback. 

121
00:11:40,480 --> 00:11:46,240
Price pulls back to test the line. At the 
same time, we have minor support from a  

122
00:11:46,240 --> 00:11:53,440
previous swing high right in that area. Not a 
major level, but enough to create confluence. 

123
00:11:53,440 --> 00:11:58,240
Watch what happens. Price barely 
touches the confluence area before  

124
00:11:58,240 --> 00:12:06,080
exploding higher. The bounce is immediate 
and powerful. No hesitation, no false moves. 

125
00:12:06,080 --> 00:12:09,360
Entry comes on the next candle after that strong  

126
00:12:09,360 --> 00:12:15,840
rejection. Price closed well above the 
moving average, confirming the bounce. 

127
00:12:15,840 --> 00:12:21,680
But more importantly, this was just one 
of the similar bounces during this trend. 

128
00:12:21,680 --> 00:12:27,600
Strong trends offer multiple confluence 
opportunities. Each time price pulls back  

129
00:12:27,600 --> 00:12:34,720
to test the moving average near a minor support 
area, you get another high-probability setup. 

130
00:12:34,720 --> 00:12:40,400
The key difference in trending markets 
is speed. The bounces happen faster and  

131
00:12:40,400 --> 00:12:46,720
move further. The trend momentum carries 
price away from confluence zones quickly. 

132
00:12:46,720 --> 00:12:50,320
You have to be ready to act 
when these setups appear. 

133
00:12:50,320 --> 00:12:54,960
This is why confluence trading works 
so well. You're not trying to predict  

134
00:12:54,960 --> 00:13:02,464
where trends will start or end. You're simply 
riding the pullbacks within existing trends.

135
00:13:02,464 --> 00:13:05,440
The Failed Trade
Now let me show you what happens when confluence  

136
00:13:05,440 --> 00:13:12,080
doesn't work. Because even the best setups fail 
sometimes, and you need to know how to handle it. 

137
00:13:12,080 --> 00:13:20,640
Euro Yen, 1-hour chart. Beautiful setup forming. 
Previous resistance turned into a strong support. 

138
00:13:20,640 --> 00:13:26,320
The 50 moving average angling up and 
converging right at that support level. 

139
00:13:26,320 --> 00:13:33,920
Perfect confluence. Price approaches from 
above, touches the zone, and... keeps falling. 

140
00:13:33,920 --> 00:13:40,160
No bounce. No respect for the confluence. 
Price slices right through both the static  

141
00:13:40,160 --> 00:13:44,480
support and the dynamic support 
like they weren't even there. 

142
00:13:44,480 --> 00:13:49,840
You will get those trades.
Here's what I learned from many failed trades,  

143
00:13:49,840 --> 00:13:56,480
which initially looked like perfect signals.
Sometimes large institutional orders are  

144
00:13:56,480 --> 00:14:01,920
placed beyond your levels. When a big 
bank decides to dump a large position,  

145
00:14:01,920 --> 00:14:07,600
your technical levels won't stop them.
And sometimes, you just picked the wrong  

146
00:14:07,600 --> 00:14:13,680
level. Maybe that support wasn't as strong 
as you thought. Maybe the confluence wasn't  

147
00:14:13,680 --> 00:14:18,000
as significant as it appeared.
And that's the game…you don't  

148
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:23,920
need every trade to work. You just need 
the winners to be bigger than the losers. 

149
00:14:23,920 --> 00:14:27,760
But the key lesson is to 
never chase a failed trade. 

150
00:14:27,760 --> 00:14:31,200
When price breaks through your 
confluence zone, you accept the  

151
00:14:31,200 --> 00:14:36,960
loss and wait for the next opportunity.
Don't try to "fix" the trade by moving  

152
00:14:36,960 --> 00:14:44,622
your stop or adding to the position. When 
the setup fails, it fails. And you move on.

153
00:14:44,622 --> 00:14:46,080
SYSTEM INTEGRATION
Let's lock this in.  

154
00:14:46,080 --> 00:14:53,120
You now have the ability to identify the only 
two levels that matter, static and dynamic.  

155
00:14:53,120 --> 00:14:58,240
You have a simple system for marking 
the strongest zones on any chart. 

156
00:14:58,240 --> 00:15:02,880
And the exact entry rules that 
keep you out of bad trades. 

157
00:15:02,880 --> 00:15:08,480
You now see the markets through the lens 
of confluence, and that changes everything.

